<div class=Section1>

<p class=MsoBodyText><span lang=EN-US>Multiple Climate Equilibria and the Runaway
Greenhouse in Moist Atmospheres</span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US style='color:black'>Nilton O. Renno</span><span
lang=EN-US> (University of Michigan)</span><span style='mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'><span
class=msoIns><ins cite="mailto:nrenno" datetime="2005-12-14T19:57"><o:p></o:p></ins></span></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>I review observations and parameterizations
of moist convection. I show that the entraining plume model is inconsistent with
observations. Moreover, I show evidence that climate equilibria is extremely
sensitive to water transport and therefore the parameterization of moist
convection. Then, I use a radiative-convective model to study the equilibria
conditions of moist atmospheres. </span><span style='mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>I show that a subcritical bifurcation
produces two linearly stable climate solutions. Thus, when the solar forcing is
larger than a critical value, a finite amplitude instability lead to two very
distinct climate equilibria. The first equilibrium corresponds to an optically
thin atmosphere. In this regime, the climate system is nearly linear and is in
a state of minimum dissipation. The second equilibrium corresponds to an
optically thick atmosphere. In this regime, the system is highly nonlinear and
is in a state of large dissipation.</span><span style='mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US>Finally, I show that another finite
amplitude instability can lead to runaway greenhouse when the solar forcing is
larger than a second critical value. I show that runaway greenhouse occurs for
values of the net solar forcing of about 290 W/m<sup>2</sup>. This value is
almost 100 W/m<sup>2</sup> lower than that predicted by Komabayasi (1967) and
Ingersoll (1969).</span><span style='mso-ansi-language:EN-GB'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span lang=EN-US><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

